abs550aer_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Optical thickness of atmospheric aerosols at wavelength 550 nanometers.
abs550aer_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Ambient Aerosol Absorption Optical Thickness at 550nm

acabf_mon-li-tav-z0-hxyA.comment: Specific mass balance means the net rate at which ice is added per unit area at the land ice surface. Computed as the total surface mass balance on the land ice portion of the grid cell divided by land ice area in the grid cell. A negative value means loss of ice

acabf_mon-li-tav-z0-hxyG.comment: Specific mass balance means the net rate at which ice is added per unit area at the land ice surface. Computed as the total surface mass balance on the land ice portion of the grid cell divided by land ice area in the grid cell. A negative value means loss of ice

acabf_yr-li-tav-z0-hxyA.comment: Specific mass balance means the net rate at which ice is added per unit area at the land ice surface. Computed as the total surface mass balance on the land ice portion of the grid cell divided by land ice area in the grid cell. A negative value means loss of ice

acabf_yr-li-tav-z0-hxyG.comment: Specific mass balance means the net rate at which ice is added per unit area at the land ice surface. Computed as the total surface mass balance on the land ice portion of the grid cell divided by land ice area in the grid cell. A negative value means loss of ice

acabfIs_mon-li-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Specific mass balance means the net rate at which ice is added per unit area at the land ice surface. Computed as the total surface mass balance on the land ice portion of the grid cell divided by land ice area in the grid cell. A negative value means loss of ice
acabfIs_mon-li-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Ice Sheet Surface Mass Balance Flux

aerasymbnd_3hr-ap-tpt-l-hxy.comment: The asymmetry factor is the angular integral of the aerosol scattering phase function weighted by the cosine of the angle with the incident radiation flux. The asymmetry coefficient is here an integral over all wavelength bands.
aerasymbnd_3hr-ap-tpt-l-hxy.long_name: Aerosol Level Asymmetry Parameter for Each Band

aeroptbnd_3hr-ap-tpt-l-hxy.comment: Optical thickness of atmospheric aerosols in wavelength bands.
aeroptbnd_3hr-ap-tpt-l-hxy.long_name: Aerosol Level Absorption Optical Thickness for Each Band

aerssabnd_3hr-ap-tpt-l-hxy.comment: The single scattering albedo is the fraction of radiation in an incident light beam scattered by the particles of an aerosol reference volume for a given wavelength. It is the ratio of the scattering and the extinction coefficients of the aerosol particles in the reference volume.
aerssabnd_3hr-ap-tpt-l-hxy.long_name: Aerosol Level Single Scattering Albedo for Each Band

agesno_day-li-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
agesno_day-li-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Age of Snow (when computing the time-mean here, the time samples, weighted by the mass of snow on the land portion of the grid cell, are accumulated and then divided by the sum of the weights.  Reported as missing data in regions free of snow on land.

albc_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Albedo of the vegetation: fraction of incoming solar radiation which is reflected before reaching the ground.

albdiffbnd_3hr-ap-tpt-z0-hxy.comment: The fraction of the surface diffuse downwelling shortwave radiation flux which is reflected. If the diffuse radiation is isotropic, this term is equivalent to the integral of surface bidirectional reflectance over all incident angles and over all outgoing angles in the hemisphere above the surface. Reported in spectral frequency bands.
albdiffbnd_3hr-ap-tpt-z0-hxy.long_name: Diffuse Surface Albedo for Each Band

albdirbnd_3hr-ap-tpt-z0-hxy.comment: The fraction of the surface direct downwelling shortwave radiation flux which is reflected. It is equivalent to the surface bidirectional reflectance at the incident angle of the incoming solar radiation and integrated over all outgoing angles in the hemisphere above the surface.  Reported in spectral frequency bands.
albdirbnd_3hr-ap-tpt-z0-hxy.long_name: Direct Surface Albedo for Each Band

albisccp_day-ap-tav-z0-hxy.comment: ISCCP Mean Cloud Albedo. Time-means are weighted by the ISCCP Total Cloud Fraction {:cltisccp} - see  http://cfmip.metoffice.com/COSP.html

albisccp_mon-ap-tav-z0-hxy.comment: ISCCP Mean Cloud Albedo. Time-means are weighted by the ISCCP Total Cloud Fraction {:cltisccp} - see  http://cfmip.metoffice.com/COSP.html

aoanh_mon-ae-tav-l-hxy.comment: Fixed surface layer mixing ratio over 30o-50oN (0 ppbv), uniform fixed source (at all levels) everywhere else (source is unspecified but must be constant in space and time and documented). Note that the source could be 1yr/yr, so the tracer concentration provides mean age in years. For method using linearly increasing tracer include a method attribute: 'linearly increasing tracer'For method using uniform source (1yr/yr) include a method attribute: 'uniform source'

cLitter_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean

The sum of the quantities with standard names surface_litter_mass_content_of_carbon and subsurface_litter_mass_content_of_carbon has the standard name litter_mass_content_of_carbon.

cLitter_yr-ld-tpt-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: point

The sum of the quantities with standard names surface_litter_mass_content_of_carbon and subsurface_litter_mass_content_of_carbon has the standard name litter_mass_content_of_carbon.

'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area. cProduct_yr-ld-tpt-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: point

cProductLut_yr-ld-tpt-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sector time: point
cProductLut_yr-ld-tpt-z0-hxy.comment: Anthropogenic pools associated with land use tiles into which harvests and cleared carbon are deposited before release into atmosphere PLUS any remaining anthropogenic pools that may be associated with lands which were converted into land use tiles during reported period. Examples of products include paper, cardboard, timber for construction, and crop harvest for food or fuel. Does NOT include residue which is deposited into soil or litter; end of year values (not annual mean).
cProductLut_yr-ld-tpt-z0-hxy.long_name: Wood and Agricultural Product Pool Carbon Associated with Land-Use Tiles

cRoot_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
cRoot_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Carbon mass per unit area in roots, including fine and coarse roots.

cSoil_yr-ld-tpt-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: point

cSoilFast_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
cSoilFast_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Carbon mass per unit area in fast soil pool. Fast means a lifetime of less than 10 years for reference climate conditions (20th century) in the absence of water limitations.
cSoilFast_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Carbon Mass in Fast Soil Pool

cSoilGrass_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: time: mean where natural_grasses (comment: mask=grassFrac)
cSoilGrass_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: 'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area. The 'soil content' of a quantity refers to the vertical integral from the surface down to the bottom of the soil model. For the content between specified levels in the soil, standard names including content_of_soil_layer are used.

cSoilLevels_mon-ld-tav-l-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean

ccb_day-ap-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Where convective cloud is present in the grid cell, the instantaneous cloud base altitude should be that of the bottom of the lowest level containing convective cloud. Missing data should be reported in the absence of convective cloud. The time mean should be calculated from these quantities averaging over occasions when convective cloud is present only, and should contain missing data for occasions when no convective cloud is present during the meaning period.
ccb_day-ap-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Air Pressure at Convective Cloud Base

ccb_mon-ap-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Where convective cloud is present in the grid cell, the instantaneous cloud base altitude should be that of the bottom of the lowest level containing convective cloud. Missing data should be reported in the absence of convective cloud. The time mean should be calculated from these quantities averaging over occasions when convective cloud is present only, and should contain missing data for occasions when no convective cloud is present during the meaning period.
ccb_mon-ap-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Air Pressure at Convective Cloud Base

ccb_subhr-ap-tpt-z0-hxys.comment: Where convective cloud is present in the grid cell, the instantaneous cloud base altitude should be that of the bottom of the lowest level containing convective cloud. ccb_subhr-ap-tpt-z0-hxys.long_name: Air Pressure at Convective Cloud Base

ccldncl_day-ap-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Droplets are liquid only.  Report concentration 'as seen from space' over convective liquid cloudy portion of grid cell.  This is the value from uppermost model layer with liquid cloud or, if available, it is better to sum over all liquid cloud tops, no matter where they occur, as long as they are seen from the top of the atmosphere. Weight by total liquid cloud top fraction of  (as seen from TOA) each time sample when computing monthly mean.
ccldncl_day-ap-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Cloud Droplet Number Concentration of Convective Cloud Tops

ccn_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Cloud Condensation Nuclei Concentration at Liquid Cloud Top

cct_day-ap-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Where convective cloud is present in the grid cell, the instantaneous cloud top altitude should be that of the top of the highest level containing convective cloud. Missing data should be reported in the absence of convective cloud. The time mean should be calculated from these quantities averaging over occasions when convective cloud is present only, and should contain missing data for occasions when no convective cloud is present during the meaning period.
cct_day-ap-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Air Pressure at Convective Cloud Top

cfadDbze94_3hr-ap-tpt-z40-hxy.comment: CFAD (Cloud Frequency Altitude Diagrams) are frequency distributions of radar  reflectivity (or lidar scattering ratio) as a function of altitude. The variable cfadDbze94 is defined as the simulated relative frequency of occurrence of radar reflectivity in sampling volumes defined by altitude bins. The radar is observing at a frequency of 94GHz.

The radar is observing at a frequency of 94GHz.

cfc11_mon-op-tav-l-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
cfc11_mon-op-tav-l-hxy.comment: Mole concentration means number of moles per unit volume, also called 'molarity', and is used in the construction 'mole_concentration_of_X_in_Y', where X is a material constituent of Y. A chemical or biological species denoted by X may be described by a single term such as 'nitrogen' or a phrase such as 'nox_expressed_as_nitrogen'. The chemical formula of CFC11 is CFCl3. The IUPAC name for CFC11 is trichloro-fluoro-methane.
cfc11_mon-op-tav-l-hxy.long_name: Mole Concentration of CFC11 in Sea Water

ch3coch3_mon-ae-tav-l-hxy.comment: Mole fraction is used in the construction 'mole_fraction_of_X_in_Y', where X is a material constituent of Y. A chemical species denoted by X may be described by a single term such as 'nitrogen' or a phrase such as 'nox_expressed_as_nitrogen'. Acetone is an organic molecule with the chemical formula CH3CH3CO. The IUPAC name for acetone is propan-2-one. Acetone is a member of the group of organic compounds known as ketones. There are standard names for the ketone group as well as for some of the individual species.

cldnci_day-ap-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Concentration 'as seen from space' over ice-cloud portion of grid cell.  This is the value from uppermost model layer with ice cloud or, if available, it is the sum over all ice cloud tops, no matter where they occur, as long as they are seen from the top of the atmosphere. Weight by total ice cloud top fraction (as seen from TOA) of each time sample when computing monthly mean.
cldnci_day-ap-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Ice Crystal Number Concentration of Cloud Tops

cldnci_mon-ap-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Concentration 'as seen from space' over ice-cloud portion of grid cell.  This is the value from uppermost model layer with ice cloud or, if available, it is the sum over all ice cloud tops, no matter where they occur, as long as they are seen from the top of the atmosphere. Weight by total ice cloud top fraction (as seen from TOA) of each time sample when computing monthly mean.
cldnci_mon-ap-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Ice Crystal Number Concentration of Cloud Tops

cldncl_mon-ap-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Droplets are liquid only.  Report concentration 'as seen from space' over liquid cloudy portion of grid cell.  This is the value from uppermost model layer with liquid cloud or, if available, it is better to sum over all liquid cloud tops, no matter where they occur, as long as they are seen from the top of the atmosphere. Weight by total liquid cloud top fraction of  (as seen from TOA) each time sample when computing monthly mean.

cldnvi_day-ap-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Droplets are liquid only.  Values are weighted by liquid cloud fraction in each layer when vertically integrating, and for monthly means the samples are weighted by total liquid cloud fraction (as seen from TOA).

cldnvi_mon-ap-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Droplets are liquid only.  Values are weighted by liquid cloud fraction in each layer when vertically integrating, and for monthly means the samples are weighted by total liquid cloud fraction (as seen from TOA).

cod_day-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: The optical thickness is the integral along the path of radiation of a volume scattering/absorption/attenuation coefficient. The radiative flux is reduced by a factor exp(-optical_thickness) on traversing the path. A coordinate variable of radiation_wavelength or radiation_frequency can be specified to indicate that the optical thickness applies at specific wavelengths or frequencies. The atmosphere optical thickness applies to radiation passing through the entire atmosphere. 'Cloud' means the component of extinction owing to the presence of liquid or ice water particles. The specification of a physical process by the phrase due_to_process means that the quantity named is a  single term in a sum of terms which together compose the general quantity named by omitting the phrase.

cod_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: The optical thickness is the integral along the path of radiation of a volume scattering/absorption/attenuation coefficient. The radiative flux is reduced by a factor exp(-optical_thickness) on traversing the path. A coordinate variable of radiation_wavelength or radiation_frequency can be specified to indicate that the optical thickness applies at specific wavelengths or frequencies. The atmosphere optical thickness applies to radiation passing through the entire atmosphere. 'Cloud' means the component of extinction owing to the presence of liquid or ice water particles. The specification of a physical process by the phrase due_to_process means that the quantity named is a  single term in a sum of terms which together compose the general quantity named by omitting the phrase.

conccmcn_mon-ap-tav-l-hxy.comment: includes all particles with diameter larger than 1 micron

conccn_mon-ap-tav-l-hxy.comment: 'Number concentration' means the number of particles or other specified objects per unit volume. 'Aerosol' means the system of suspended liquid or solid particles in air (except cloud droplets) and their carrier gas, the air itself. 'Ambient_aerosol' means that the aerosol is measured or modelled at the ambient state of pressure, temperature and relative humidity that exists in its immediate environment. 'Ambient aerosol particles' are aerosol particles that have taken up ambient water through hygroscopic growth. The extent of hygroscopic growth depends on the relative humidity and the composition of the particles.

concdust_mon-ap-tav-l-hxy.comment: Mass concentration means mass per unit volume and is used in the construction mass_concentration_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y. A chemical species denoted by X may be described by a single term such as 'nitrogen' or a phrase such as 'nox_expressed_as_nitrogen'. 'Aerosol' means the system of suspended liquid or solid particles in air (except cloud droplets) and their carrier gas, the air itself. Aerosol particles take up ambient water (a process known as hygroscopic growth) depending on the relative humidity and the composition of the particles. 'Dry aerosol particles' means aerosol particles without any water uptake.

concnmcn_mon-ap-tav-l-hxy.comment: includes all particles with diameter smaller than 3 nm
concnmcn_mon-ap-tav-l-hxy.long_name: Number Concentration of Nucleation Mode Aerosol

Contributions to this additional drag such Rayleigh friction and diffusion that can be calculated from the monthly mean wind fields should not be included, but details (e.g. coefficients) of the friction and/or diffusion used in the model should be provided separately.

diftrxybo_mon-op-tcla-l-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean time: mean within years time: mean over years
diftrxybo_mon-op-tcla-l-hxy.comment: Diffusivity is also sometimes known as the coefficient of diffusion. Diffusion occurs as a result of a gradient in the spatial distribution of mass concentration, temperature or momentum.  The diffusivity may be very different in the vertical and horizontal directions. 'xy diffusivity' means the lateral along_coordinate component of diffusivity due to motion which is not resolved on the grid scale of the model.  xy diffusivities are used in some ocean models to counteract the numerical instabilities inherent in certain implementations of rotated neutral diffusion. 'biharmonic diffusivity' means diffusivity for use with a biharmonic diffusion operator.

difvmto_mon-op-tcla-l-hxy.comment: Diffusivity is also sometimes known as the coefficient of diffusion. Diffusion occurs as a result of a gradient in the spatial distribution of mass concentration, temperature or momentum.  The diffusivity may be very different in the vertical and horizontal directions. The construction vertical_X_diffusivity means the vertical component of the diffusivity of X due to motion which is not resolved on the grid scale of the model. 'Due to tides' means due to all astronomical gravity changes which manifest as tides. No distinction is made between different tidal components. The specification of a physical process by the phrase due_to_process means that the quantity named is a  single term in a sum of terms which together compose the general quantity  named by omitting the phrase.

dispkevfo_mon-op-tcla-l-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean time: mean within years time: mean over years
dispkevfo_mon-op-tcla-l-hxy.comment: Friction, leading to the dissipation of kinetic energy, arises in ocean models as a result of the viscosity of sea water.  Generally, the  lateral (xy) viscosity is given a large value to maintain the numerical stability of the model.  In contrast, the vertical viscosity is usually much smaller. The specification of a physical process by the phrase due_to_process means that the quantity named is a  single term in a sum of terms which together compose the general quantity  named by omitting the phrase.
dispkevfo_mon-op-tcla-l-hxy.long_name: Ocean Kinetic Energy Dissipation per Unit Area Due to Vertical Friction

dispkexyfo_mon-op-tcla-l-hxy.comment: Depth integrated impacts on kinetic energy arising from lateral frictional dissipation associated with Laplacian and/or biharmonic viscosity. For CMIP5, this diagnostic was 3d, whereas the CMIP6 depth integrated diagnostic is sufficient for many purposes and reduces archive requirements.
dispkexyfo_mon-op-tcla-l-hxy.long_name: Ocean Kinetic Energy Dissipation per Unit Area Due to XY Friction

dmc_mon-ap-tav-l-hxy.comment: The net mass flux  represents the difference between the updraft and downdraft components.   This is calculated as the convective mass flux divided by the area of the whole grid cell (not just the area of the cloud).

dmlt_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Depth from surface to the zero degree isotherm. Above this isotherm T > 0o, and below this line T < 0o. Missing if surface is frozen or if soil is unfrozen at all depths.

dms_mon-ae-tav-l-hxy.comment: Mole fraction is used in the construction mole_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.

dmso_mon-oc-tav-l-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
dmso_mon-oc-tav-l-hxy.comment: Mole concentration of dimethyl sulphide in water
dmso_mon-oc-tav-l-hxy.long_name: Mole Concentration of Dimethyl Sulphide in Sea Water

dmso_yr-oc-tav-l-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
dmso_yr-oc-tav-l-hxy.comment: Mole concentration of dimethyl sulphide in water
dmso_yr-oc-tav-l-hxy.long_name: Mole Concentration of Dimethyl Sulphide in Sea Water

dmsos_mon-oc-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Surface Mole Concentration of Dimethyl Sulphide in Sea Water

dpco2_mon-oc-tav-z00-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
dpco2_mon-oc-tav-z00-hxy.comment: Difference in partial pressure of carbon dioxide between sea water and air.  The partial pressure of a dissolved gas in sea water is the partial pressure in air with which it would be in equilibrium.

dpco2abio_mon-oc-tav-z00-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
dpco2abio_mon-oc-tav-z00-hxy.comment: Difference in partial pressure of abiotic-analogue carbon dioxide between sea water and air.  The partial pressure of a dissolved gas in sea water is the partial pressure in air with which it would be in equilibrium. An abiotic analogue is used to simulate the effect on a modelled variable when biological effects on ocean carbon concentration and alkalinity are ignored.

dpco2nat_mon-oc-tav-z00-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
dpco2nat_mon-oc-tav-z00-hxy.comment: Difference in partial pressure of natural-analogue carbon dioxide between sea water and air.  The partial pressure of a dissolved gas in sea water is the partial pressure in air with which it would be in equilibrium.  A natural analogue is used to simulate the effect on a modelled variable of imposing preindustrial atmospheric carbon dioxide concentrations, even when the model as a whole may be subjected to varying forcings.

dpo2_mon-oc-tav-z00-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
dpo2_mon-oc-tav-z00-hxy.comment: The partial pressure of a dissolved gas in sea water is the partial pressure in air with which it would be in equilibrium.  The partial pressure of a gaseous constituent of air is the pressure which it alone would exert with unchanged temperature and number of moles per unit volume.  The surface called 'surface' means the lower boundary of the atmosphere.

drivw_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
drivw_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Change over time of the mass of water per unit area in the fluvial system (stream and floodplain).

drybc_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Dry deposition includes gravitational settling and turbulent deposition.

drydust_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Dry deposition includes gravitational settling and turbulent deposition.

drynh3_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Dry Deposition includes gravitational settling and turbulent deposition

drynh4_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Dry Deposition includes gravitational settling and turbulent deposition

drynoy_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: NOy is the sum of all simulated oxidized nitrogen species out of NO, NO2, HNO3, HNO4, NO3 aerosol, NO3(radical), N2O5, PAN, other organic nitrates. Dry deposition includes gravitational settling and turbulent deposition.

dryo3_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Dry Deposition includes gravitational settling and turbulent deposition.

dryoa_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Tendency of atmosphere mass content of organic dry aerosol due to dry deposition: This is the sum of dry deposition of primary organic aerosol (POA) and dry deposition of secondary organic aerosol (SOA). Here, mass refers to the mass of organic matter, not mass of organic carbon alone.  We recommend a scale factor of POM=1.4*OC, unless your model has more detailed info available. Was called dry_pom in old ACCMIP Excel table. Dry deposition includes gravitational settling and turbulent deposition.
dryoa_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Dry Deposition Rate of Dry Aerosol Total Organic Matter

dryso2_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Dry Deposition includes gravitational settling and turbulent deposition

dryso4_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Dry Deposition includes gravitational settling and turbulent deposition

dryss_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Dry deposition includes gravitational settling and turbulent deposition.
dryss_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Dry Deposition Rate of Sea-Salt Aerosol

dslw_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
dslw_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: The phrase 'change_over_time_in_X' means change in a quantity X over a time-interval, which should be defined by the bounds of the time coordinate. 'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area. The mass content of water in soil refers to the vertical integral from the surface down to the bottom of the soil model. For the content between specified levels in the soil, standard names including 'content_of_soil_layer' are used. 'Water' means water in all phases.

dsn_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
dsn_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Change in time of the mass per unit area of ice in glaciers, ice caps, ice sheets and shelves, river and lake ice, any other ice on a land surface, such as frozen flood water, and snow lying on such ice or on the land surface.

dsw_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
dsw_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: The phrase 'land_water_amount', often known as 'Terrestrial Water Storage', includes: surface liquid water (water in rivers, wetlands, lakes, reservoirs, rainfall intercepted by the canopy); surface ice and snow (glaciers, ice caps, grounded ice sheets not displacing sea water, river and lake ice, other surface ice such as frozen flood water, snow lying on the surface and intercepted by the canopy); subsurface water (liquid and frozen soil water, groundwater).

dtauc_3hr-ap-tpt-l-hxy.comment: This is the in-cloud optical depth obtained by considering only the cloudy portion of the grid cell

dtauc_6hr-ap-tpt-z0-hxy.comment: This is the in-cloud optical depth obtained by considering only the cloudy portion of the grid cell

dtaus_3hr-ap-tpt-l-hxy.comment: This is the in-cloud optical depth obtained by considering only the cloudy portion of the grid cell.

dtaus_6hr-ap-tpt-z0-hxy.comment: This is the in-cloud optical depth obtained by considering only the cloudy portion of the grid cell.

dtes_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
dtes_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Change in heat storage over the soil layer and the vegetation for which the energy balance is calculated, accumulated over the sampling time interval.

dtesn_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
dtesn_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Change in cold content over the snow layer for which the energy balance is calculated, accumulated over the sampling time interval. This should also include the energy contained in the liquid water in the snow pack.
dtesn_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Change in Snow and Ice Cold Content

ec_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean

emiaoa_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Emission Rate of Anthropogenic Organic Aerosol

emibc_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Emission Rate of Black Carbon Aerosol Mass

emibvoc_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Integrate 3D emission field vertically to 2d field._If_ fixed molecular weight of NMVOC is not available in model, please provide in units of kilomole m-2 s-1 (i.e. kg m-2 s-1 as if model NMVOC had molecular weight of 1) and add a comment to your file.

emico_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Integrate 3D emission field vertically to 2d field.

emidms_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Integrate 3D emission field vertically to 2d field.

emiisop_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Integrate 3D emission field vertically to 2d field

eminh3_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Integrate 3D emission field vertically to 2d field.

eminox_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: NOx=NO+NO2. Integrate 3D emission field vertically to 2d field.

emioa_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: This is the sum of total emission of primary organic aerosol (POA) and total production of secondary organic aerosol (SOA) (emipoa+chepsoa). Here, mass refers to the mass of organic matter, not mass of organic carbon alone. We recommend a scale factor of POM=1.4*OC, unless your model has more detailed info available.  Integrate 3D chemical production and emission field vertically to 2d field.
emioa_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Primary Emission and Chemical Production of Dry Aerosol Organic Matter

emiso2_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Integrate 3D emission field vertically to 2d field.

emiso4_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Direct primary emission does not include secondary sulfate production. Integrate 3D emission field vertically to 2d field.

emiss_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Emission Rate of Sea-Salt Aerosol

emivoc_mon-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Integrate 3D emission field vertically to 2d field. _If_ fixed molecular weight of NMVOC is not available in model, please provide in units of kilomole m-2 s-1 (i.e. kg m-2 s-1 as if model NMVOC had molecular weight of 1) and add a comment to your file.

eparag100_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
eparag100_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.comment: The phrase 'expressed_as' is used in the construction A_expressed_as_B, where B is a chemical constituent of A. It means that the quantity indicated by the standard name is calculated solely with respect to the B contained in A, neglecting all other chemical constituents of A. In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics.   'Sinking' is the gravitational settling of particulate matter suspended in a liquid. A sinking flux is positive downwards and is calculated relative to the movement of the surrounding fluid. Aragonite is a mineral that is a polymorph of calcium carbonate. The chemical formula of aragonite is CaCO3. Standard names also exist for calcite, another polymorph of calcium carbonate.

epfy_day-ap-tav-p39-hy.comment: Transformed Eulerian Mean Diagnostics Meridional component Fy of Eliassen-Palm (EP) flux (Fy, Fz) derived from 6hr or higher frequency fields (use daily fields or 12 hr fields if the 6 hr are not available). es_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
es_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Water here means water in all phases. Evaporation is the conversion of liquid or solid into vapor. (The conversion of solid alone into vapor is called 'sublimation'.) esn_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
esn_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Water here means water in all phases. Evaporation is the conversion of liquid or solid into vapor. (The conversion of solid alone into vapor is called 'sublimation'.) In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics. Unless indicated in the cell_methods attribute, a quantity is assumed to apply to the whole area of each horizontal grid box. Previously, the qualifier where_type was used to specify that the quantity applies only to the part of the grid box of the named type.  Names containing the where_type qualifier are deprecated and newly created data should use the cell_methods attribute to indicate the horizontal area to which the quantity applies.

evs_mon-op-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Water Evaporation Flux Where Ice Free Ocean over Sea

fCLandToOcean_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Lateral Transfer of Carbon out of Grid Cell That Eventually Goes into Ocean

fDeforestToAtmos_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fDeforestToAtmos_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: When land use change results in deforestation of natural vegetation (trees or grasslands) then natural biomass is removed. The treatment of deforested biomass differs significantly across models, but it should be straight-forward to compare deforested biomass across models.
fDeforestToAtmos_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Deforested Biomass That Goes into Atmosphere as a Result of Anthropogenic Land-Use Change [kgC m-2 s-1]

fDeforestToProduct_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fDeforestToProduct_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: When land use change results in deforestation of natural vegetation (trees or grasslands) then natural biomass is removed. The treatment of deforested biomass differs significantly across models, but it should be straight-forward to compare deforested biomass across models.
fDeforestToProduct_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Deforested Biomass That Goes into Product Pool as a Result of Anthropogenic Land-Use Change

fFire_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fFire_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: CO2 emissions (expressed as a carbon mass flux per unit area) from natural fires and human ignition fires as calculated by the fire module of the dynamic vegetation model, but excluding any CO2 flux from fire included in fLuc (CO2 Flux to Atmosphere from Land Use Change).
fFire_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux into Atmosphere Due to CO2 Emission from Fire Excluding Land-Use Change [kgC m-2 s-1]

fFireAll_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fFireAll_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: From all sources,  Including natural, anthropogenic and Land-use change. Only total fire emissions can be compared to observations.
fFireAll_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux into Atmosphere Due to CO2 Emission from Fire Including All Sources [kgC m-2 s-1]

fFireNat_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fFireNat_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux into Atmosphere Due to CO2 Emission from Natural Fire [kgC m-2 s-1]

fGrazing_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fGrazing_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Carbon mass flux per unit area due to grazing on land
fGrazing_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux into Atmosphere Due to Grazing on Land [kgC m-2 s-1]

fHarvest_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fHarvest_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Carbon mass flux per unit area due to crop harvesting
fHarvest_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux into Atmosphere Due to Crop Harvesting [kgC m-2 s-1]

fHarvestToAtmos_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fHarvestToAtmos_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: any harvested carbon that is assumed to decompose immediately into the atmosphere is reported here
fHarvestToAtmos_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Harvested Biomass That Goes Straight into Atmosphere as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

fHarvestToProduct_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fHarvestToProduct_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: be it food or wood harvest, any carbon that is subsequently stored is reported here
fHarvestToProduct_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Harvested Biomass That Goes into Product Pool

fLitterFire_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fLitterFire_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Required for unambiguous separation of vegetation and soil + litter turnover times, since total fire flux draws from both sources
fLitterFire_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux from Litter, CWD or any non-Living Pool into Atmosphere Due to CO2 Emission from All Fire [kgC m-2 s-1]

fLitterSoil_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fLitterSoil_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Carbon mass flux per unit area into soil from litter (dead plant material in or above the soil).
fLitterSoil_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Carbon Mass Flux from Litter to Soil

fLuc_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fLuc_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Carbon mass flux per unit area into atmosphere due to human changes to land (excluding forest regrowth) accounting possibly for different time-scales related to fate of the wood, for example.
fLuc_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Net Carbon Mass Flux into Atmosphere Due to Land-Use Change [kgC m-2 s-1]

fLulccAtmLut_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: This annual mean flux refers to the transfer of carbon directly to the atmosphere due to any land-use or land-cover change activities.  Include carbon transferred due to deforestation or agricultural directly into atmosphere, and  emissions form anthropogenic pools into atmosphere
fLulccAtmLut_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Carbon Transferred Directly to Atmosphere Due to any Land-Use or Land-Cover Change Activities [kgC m-2 s-1]

fLulccProductLut_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: This annual mean flux refers to the transfer of carbon primarily through harvesting land use into anthropogenic product pools, e.g.,deforestation or wood harvesting from primary or secondary lands, food harvesting on croplands, harvesting (grazing) by animals on pastures.
fLulccProductLut_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Carbon Harvested Due to Land-Use or Land-Cover Change Process That Enters Anthropogenic Product Pools on Tile

fLulccResidueLut_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: This annual mean flux refers to the transfer of carbon into soil or litter pools due to any land use or land-cover change activities
fLulccResidueLut_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Carbon Transferred to Soil or Litter Pools Due to Land-Use or Land-Cover Change Processes on Tile

fN2O_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fN2O_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Surface upward flux of nitrous oxide (N2O) from vegetation (any living plants e.g. trees, shrubs, grass), litter (dead plant material in or above the soil), soil.

fNAnthDisturb_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fNAnthDisturb_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: will require some careful definition to make sure we capture everything - any human activity that releases nitrogen from land  instead of into product pool goes here. E.g. Deforestation fire, harvest assumed to decompose straight away, grazing...
fNAnthDisturb_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Nitrogen Mass Flux out of Land Due to any Human Activity

fNLandToOcean_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fNLandToOcean_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: leached nitrogen etc that goes into run off or river routing and finds its way into ocean should be reported here.
fNLandToOcean_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Lateral Transfer of Nitrogen out of Grid Cell That Eventually Goes into Ocean

fNLitterSoil_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fNLitterSoil_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics. 'Litter' is dead plant material in or above the soil.
fNLitterSoil_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Nitrogen Mass Flux from Litter to Soil

fNOx_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fNOx_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: The surface called 'surface' means the lower boundary of the atmosphere. 'Upward' indicates a vector component which is positive when directed upward (negative downward). In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics. The phrase 'expressed_as' is used in the construction A_expressed_as_B, where B is a chemical constituent of A. It means that the quantity indicated by the standard name is calculated solely with respect to the B contained in A, neglecting all other chemical constituents of A. 'Nox' means a combination of two radical species containing nitrogen and oxygen NO+NO2. 'Vegetation' means any living plants e.g. trees, shrubs, grass. 'Litter' is dead plant material in or above the soil.

fNProduct_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fNProduct_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: When land use change results in deforestation of natural vegetation (trees or grasslands) then natural biomass is removed. The treatment of deforested biomass differs significantly across models, but it should be straight-forward to compare deforested biomass across models.
fNProduct_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Deforested or Harvested Biomass as a Result of Anthropogenic Land-Use or Change

fNVegLitter_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fNVegLitter_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics. 'Litter' is dead plant material in or above the soil. 'Vegetation' means any living plants e.g. trees, shrubs, grass.
fNVegLitter_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Nitrogen Mass Flux from Vegetation to Litter

fNVegSoil_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fNVegSoil_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: In some models part of nitrogen (e.g., root exudate) can go directly into the soil pool without entering litter.
fNVegSoil_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Nitrogen Mass Flux from Vegetation Directly to Soil

fNdep_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fNdep_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Dry and Wet Deposition of Reactive Nitrogen onto Land

fNfert_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fNfert_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Total Nitrogen added for cropland fertilisation (artificial and manure). Relative to total land area of a grid cell, not relative to agricultural area
fNfert_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Nitrogen Added for Cropland Fertilisation (Artificial and Manure)

fNgas_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fNgas_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Total flux of Nitrogen from the land into the atmosphere.
fNgas_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Nitrogen Lost to the Atmosphere (Sum of NHx, NOx, N2O, N2)

fNgasFire_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fNgasFire_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Flux of Nitrogen from the land into the atmosphere due to fire
fNgasFire_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Nitrogen Lost to the Atmosphere (Including NHx, NOx, N2O, N2) from Fire

fNgasNonFire_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fNgasNonFire_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Flux of Nitrogen from the land into the atmosphere due to all processes other than fire
fNgasNonFire_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Nitrogen Lost to the Atmosphere (Including NHx, NOx, N2O, N2) from All Processes Except Fire

fNleach_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fNleach_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics. The specification of a physical process by the phrase 'due_to_' process means that the quantity named is a single term in a sum of terms which together compose the general quantity named by omitting the phrase. 'Leaching' means the loss of water soluble chemical species from soil. Runoff is the liquid water which drains from land. If not specified, 'runoff' refers to the sum of surface runoff and subsurface drainage.
fNleach_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Nitrogen Loss to Leaching or Runoff (Sum of Ammonium, Nitrite and Nitrate)

fNloss_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fNloss_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Not all models split losses into gaseous and leaching
fNloss_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Nitrogen Lost (Including NHx, NOx, N2O, N2 and Leaching)

fNnetmin_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fNnetmin_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Loss of soil nitrogen through remineralization and immobilisation. Remineralization is the degradation of organic matter into inorganic forms of carbon, nitrogen, phosphorus and other micronutrients, which consumes oxygen and releases energy. Immobilisation of nitrogen refers to retention of nitrogen by micro-organisms under certain conditions, making it unavailable for plants.
fNnetmin_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Net Nitrogen Release from Soil and Litter as the Outcome of Nitrogen Immobilisation and Gross Mineralisation

fNup_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fNup_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: The uptake of nitrogen by fixation: nitrogen fixation means the uptake of nitrogen gas directly from the atmosphere.
fNup_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Plant Nitrogen Uptake (Sum of Ammonium and Nitrate) Irrespective of the Source of Nitrogen

fProductDecomp_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fProductDecomp_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Flux of CO2 from product pools into the atmosphere. Examples of 'forestry and agricultural products' are paper, cardboard, furniture, timber for construction, biofuels and food for both humans and livestock. Models that simulate land use changes have one or more pools of carbon that represent these products in order to conserve carbon and allow its eventual release into the atmosphere, for example, when the products decompose in landfill sites.
fProductDecomp_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Decomposition out of Product Pools to CO2 in Atmosphere as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

fProductDecompLut_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Flux of CO2 from product pools into the atmosphere. Examples of 'forestry and agricultural products' are paper, cardboard, furniture, timber for construction, biofuels and food for both humans and livestock. Models that simulate land use changes have one or more pools of carbon that represent these products in order to conserve carbon and allow its eventual release into the atmosphere, for example, when the products decompose in landfill sites. Produce this variable i  a model has explicit anthropogenic product pools by land use tile
fProductDecompLut_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Net Carbon Mass Flux from Wood and Agricultural Product Pools on Land Use Tile into Atmosphere [kgC m-2 s-1]

fVegFire_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fVegFire_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Required for unambiguous separation of vegetation and soil + litter turnover times, since total fire flux draws from both sources
fVegFire_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux from Vegetation into Atmosphere Due to CO2 Emission from All Fire [kgC m-2 s-1]

fVegLitter_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fVegLitter_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics. 'Vegetation' means any living plants e.g. trees, shrubs, grass. 'Litter' is dead plant material in or above the soil. It is distinct from coarse wood debris. The precise distinction between 'fine' and 'coarse' is model dependent. The sum of the quantities with standard names mass_flux_of_carbon_into_litter_from_vegetation_due_to_mortality and mass_flux_of_carbon_into_litter_from_vegetation_due_to_senescence is mass_flux_of_carbon_into_litter_from_vegetation.
fVegLitter_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Carbon Mass Flux from Vegetation to Litter

fVegLitterMortality_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fVegLitterMortality_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: needed to separate changing vegetation C turnover times resulting from changing allocation versus changing mortality
fVegLitterMortality_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Carbon Mass Flux from Vegetation to Litter as a Result of Mortality

fVegLitterSenescence_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fVegLitterSenescence_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: needed to separate changing vegetation C turnover times resulting from changing allocation versus changing mortality
fVegLitterSenescence_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Carbon Mass Flux from Vegetation to Litter as a Result of Leaf, Branch, and Root Senescence

fVegSoil_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fVegSoil_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Carbon mass flux per unit area from vegetation directly into soil, without intermediate conversion to litter.
fVegSoil_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Carbon Mass Flux from Vegetation Directly to Soil

fVegSoilMortality_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fVegSoilMortality_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: needed to separate changing vegetation C turnover times resulting from changing allocation versus changing mortality
fVegSoilMortality_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Carbon Mass Flux from Vegetation to Soil as a Result of Mortality

fVegSoilSenescence_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
fVegSoilSenescence_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: needed to separate changing vegetation C turnover times resulting from changing allocation versus changing mortality
fVegSoilSenescence_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Total Carbon Mass Flux from Vegetation to Soil as a Result of Leaf, Branch, and Root Senescence

fahLut_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Anthropogenic heat flux generated from non-renewable human primary energy consumption, including energy use by vehicles, commercial and residential buildings, industry, and power plants.  Primary energy refers to energy in natural resources, fossil and nonfossil, before conversion into other forms, such as electricity.
fahLut_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Anthropogenic Heat Flux Generated from non-Renewable Human Primary Energy Consumption

fbddtalk_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea depth: sum where sea (top 100m only) time: mean
fbddtalk_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.comment: vertical integral of net biological terms in time rate of change of alkalinity
fbddtalk_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.long_name: Rate of Change of Biological Alkalinity Due to Biological Activity

fbddtdic_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea depth: sum where sea (top 100m only) time: mean
fbddtdic_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.comment: vertical integral of net biological terms in time rate of change of dissolved inorganic carbon
fbddtdic_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.long_name: Rate of Change of Dissolved Inorganic Carbon Due to Biological Activity

fbddtdife_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea depth: sum where sea (top 100m only) time: mean
fbddtdife_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.comment: vertical integral of net biological terms in time rate of change of dissolved inorganic iron
fbddtdife_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.long_name: Rate of Change of Dissolved Inorganic Iron Due to Biological Activity

fbddtdin_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea depth: sum where sea (top 100m only) time: mean
fbddtdin_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.comment: vertical integral of net biological terms in time rate of change of nitrogen nutrients (e.g. NO3+NH4)
fbddtdin_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.long_name: Rate of Change of Dissolved Inorganic Nitrogen Due to Biological Activity

fbddtdip_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea depth: sum where sea (top 100m only) time: mean
fbddtdip_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.comment: vertical integral of net biological terms in time rate of change of phosphate
fbddtdip_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.long_name: Rate of Change of Dissolved Inorganic Phosphorus Due to Biological Activity

fbddtdisi_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea depth: sum where sea (top 100m only) time: mean
fbddtdisi_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.comment: vertical integral of net biological terms in time rate of change of dissolved inorganic silicate
fbddtdisi_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.long_name: Rate of Change of Dissolved Inorganic Silicon Due to Biological Activity

fco2antt_mon-ap-tav-z0-hxy.comment: This is requested only for the emission-driven coupled carbon climate model runs.  Does not include natural fire sources but, includes all anthropogenic sources, including fossil fuel use, cement production, agricultural burning, and sources associated with anthropogenic land use change excluding forest regrowth.
fco2antt_mon-ap-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux into Atmosphere Due to All Anthropogenic Emissions of CO2 [kgC m-2 s-1]

fco2antt_subhr-ap-tpt-z0-hxys.comment: This is requested only for the emission-driven coupled carbon climate model runs.  Does not include natural fire sources but, includes all anthropogenic sources, including fossil fuel use, cement production, agricultural burning, and sources associated with anthropogenic land use change excluding forest regrowth.
fco2antt_subhr-ap-tpt-z0-hxys.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux into Atmosphere Due to All Anthropogenic Emissions of CO2 [kgC m-2 s-1]

fco2fos_mon-ap-tav-z0-hxy.comment: This is the prescribed anthropogenic CO2 flux from fossil fuel use, including cement production, and flaring (but not from land-use changes, agricultural burning, forest regrowth, etc.)
fco2fos_mon-ap-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux into Atmosphere Due to Fossil Fuel Emissions of CO2 [kgC m-2 s-1]

fco2fos_subhr-ap-tpt-z0-hxys.comment: This is the prescribed anthropogenic CO2 flux from fossil fuel use, including cement production, and flaring (but not from land-use changes, agricultural burning, forest regrowth, etc.)
fco2fos_subhr-ap-tpt-z0-hxys.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux into Atmosphere Due to Fossil Fuel Emissions of CO2 [kgC m-2 s-1]

fco2nat_mon-ap-tav-z0-hxy.comment: This is what the atmosphere sees (on its own grid).  This field should be equivalent to the combined natural fluxes of carbon  that account for natural exchanges between the atmosphere and land (nep) or ocean (fgco2) reservoirs.
fco2nat_mon-ap-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Surface Carbon Mass Flux into the Atmosphere Due to Natural Sources [kgC m-2 s-1]

fco2nat_subhr-ap-tpt-z0-hxys.comment: This is what the atmosphere sees (on its own grid).  This field should be equivalent to the combined natural fluxes of carbon  that account for natural exchanges between the atmosphere and land (nep) or ocean (fgco2) reservoirs.
fco2nat_subhr-ap-tpt-z0-hxys.long_name: Surface Carbon Mass Flux into the Atmosphere Due to Natural Sources [kgC m-2 s-1]

fddtalk_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea depth: sum where sea (top 100m only) time: mean
fddtalk_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.comment: vertical integral of net time rate of change of alkalinity
fddtalk_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.long_name: Rate of Change of Total Alkalinity

fddtdic_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea depth: sum where sea (top 100m only) time: mean
fddtdic_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.comment: 'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area.  'tendency_of_X' means derivative of X with respect to time. 'Dissolved inorganic carbon' describes a family of chemical species in solution, including carbon dioxide, carbonic acid and the carbonate and bicarbonate anions. 'Dissolved inorganic carbon' is the term used in standard names for all species belonging to the family that are represented within a given model. The list of individual species that are included in a quantity having a group chemical standard name can vary between models.  Where possible, the data variable should be accompanied by a complete description of the species represented, for example, by using a comment attribute.
fddtdic_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.long_name: Rate of Change of Net Dissolved Inorganic Carbon

fddtdife_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea depth: sum where sea (top 100m only) time: mean
fddtdife_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.comment: vertical integral of net time rate of change of dissolved inorganic iron
fddtdife_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.long_name: Rate of Change of Net Dissolved Inorganic Iron

fddtdin_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea depth: sum where sea (top 100m only) time: mean
fddtdin_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.comment: Net time rate of change of nitrogen nutrients (e.g. NO3+NH4)
fddtdin_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.long_name: Rate of Change of Net Dissolved Inorganic Nitrogen

fddtdip_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea depth: sum where sea (top 100m only) time: mean
fddtdip_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.comment: vertical integral of net  time rate of change of phosphate
fddtdip_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.long_name: Rate of Change of Net Dissolved Inorganic Phosphorus

fddtdisi_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea depth: sum where sea (top 100m only) time: mean
fddtdisi_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.comment: vertical integral of net time rate of change of dissolved inorganic silicate
fddtdisi_mon-oc-tav-z0100-hxy.long_name: Rate of Change of Net Dissolved Inorganic Silicon

fediss_yr-oc-tav-l-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean

frn_mon-oc-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
frn_mon-oc-tav-z0-hxy.comment: 'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area.  The specification of a physical process by the phrase due_to_process means that the quantity named is a single term in a sum of terms which together compose the general quantity  named by omitting the phrase. 'Denitrification' is the conversion of nitrate into gaseous compounds such as nitric oxide, nitrous oxide and molecular nitrogen which are then emitted to the atmosphere.  'Sedimentation' is the sinking of particulate matter to the floor of a body of water. 'tendency_of_X' means derivative of X with respect to time.

grpllsprof_3hr-ap-tpt-l-hxy.comment: In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics. Stratiform precipitation, whether liquid or frozen, is precipitation that formed in stratiform cloud. Graupel consists of heavily rimed snow particles, often called snow pellets; often indistinguishable from very small soft hail except when the size convention that hail must have a diameter greater than 5 mm is adopted. Reference: American Meteorological Society Glossary http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Graupel. There are also separate standard names for hail. Standard names for 'graupel_and_hail' should be used to describe data produced by models that do not distinguish between hail and graupel.

hcfc22global_mon-ap-tav-z0-hm.comment: Mole fraction is used in the construction mole_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.  A chemical species denoted by X may be described by a single term such as 'nitrogen' or a phrase such as 'nox_expressed_as_nitrogen'. The chemical formula for HCFC22 is CHClF2.  The IUPAC name for HCFC22 is chloro-difluoro-methane.
hcfc22global_mon-ap-tav-z0-hm.long_name: Global Mean Mole Fraction of HCFC22

hcho_mon-ae-tav-l-hxy.comment: Mole fraction is used in the construction mole_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.

'Downward' indicates a vector component which is positive when directed downward (negative upward). The vertical heat flux in air is the sum of all heat fluxes i.e. radiative, latent and sensible. In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics.

hfls_3hr-ap-tav-z0-hxy.comment: The surface called 'surface' means the lower boundary of the atmosphere. 'Upward' indicates a vector component which is positive when directed upward (negative downward). The surface latent heat flux is the exchange of heat between the surface and the air on account of evaporation (including sublimation). In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics.

hfsifrazil_mon-op-tav-l-hxy.comment: In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics. The specification of a physical process by the phrase due_to_process means that the quantity named is a single term in a sum of terms which together compose the general quantity named by omitting the phrase. 'Frazil' consists of needle like crystals of ice, typically between three and four millimeters in diameter, which form as sea water begins to freeze. Salt is expelled during the freezing process and frazil ice consists of nearly pure fresh water.

limfecalc_mon-oc-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
limfecalc_mon-oc-tav-z0-hxy.comment: 'Calcareous phytoplankton' are phytoplankton that produce calcite. Calcite is a mineral that is a polymorph of calcium carbonate. The chemical formula of calcite is CaCO3. Phytoplankton are algae that grow where there is sufficient light to support photosynthesis. 'Iron growth limitation' means the ratio of the growth rate of a species population in the environment (where there is a finite availability of iron) to the theoretical growth rate if there were no such limit on iron availability.

limfediat_mon-oc-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
limfediat_mon-oc-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Diatoms are phytoplankton with an external skeleton made of silica. Phytoplankton are algae that grow where there is sufficient light to support photosynthesis. 'Iron growth limitation' means the ratio of the growth rate of a species population in the environment (where there is a finite availability of iron) to the theoretical growth rate if there were no such limit on iron availability.

limfediaz_mon-oc-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
limfediaz_mon-oc-tav-z0-hxy.comment: In ocean modelling, diazotrophs are phytoplankton of the phylum cyanobacteria distinct from other phytoplankton groups in their ability to fix nitrogen gas in addition to nitrate and ammonium. Phytoplankton are algae that grow where there is sufficient light to support photosynthesis. 'Iron growth limitation' means the ratio of the growth rate of a species population in the environment (where there is a finite availability of iron) to the theoretical growth rate if there were no such limit on iron availability.

limfemisc_mon-oc-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
limfemisc_mon-oc-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Phytoplankton are algae that grow where there is sufficient light to support photosynthesis. 'Miscellaneous phytoplankton' are all those phytoplankton that are not diatoms, diazotrophs, calcareous phytoplankton, picophytoplankton or other separately named components of the phytoplankton population. 'Iron growth limitation' means the ratio of the growth rate of a species population in the environment (where there is a finite availability of iron) to the theoretical growth rate if there were no such limit on iron availability.

limfepico_mon-oc-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
limfepico_mon-oc-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Picophytoplankton are phytoplankton of less than 2 micrometers in size. Phytoplankton are algae that grow where there is sufficient light to support photosynthesis. 'Iron growth limitation' means the ratio of the growth rate of a species population in the environment (where there is a finite availability of iron) to the theoretical growth rate if there were no such limit on iron availability.

limirrcalc_mon-oc-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
limirrcalc_mon-oc-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Growth limitation of calcareous phytoplankton due to solar irradiance. 'Growth limitation due to solar irradiance' means the ratio of the growth rate of a species population in the environment (where the amount of sunlight reaching a location may be limited) to the theoretical growth rate if there were no such limit on solar irradiance.

masscello_dec-op-tav-l-hxy.cell_methods: area: sum where sea time: mean
masscello_dec-op-tav-l-hxy.comment: Tracer grid-cell mass per unit area used for computing tracer budgets. For Boussinesq models with static ocean grid cell thickness, masscello = rhozero*thickcello, where thickcello is static cell thickness and rhozero is constant Boussinesq reference density. More generally, masscello is time dependent and reported as part of Omon.

masscello_fx-op-none-l-hxy.comment: Tracer grid-cell mass per unit area used for computing tracer budgets. For Boussinesq models with static ocean grid cell thickness, masscello = rhozero*thickcello, where thickcello is static cell thickness and rhozero is constant Boussinesq reference density. More generally, masscello is time dependent and reported as part of Omon.

maxpblz_day-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: maximum boundary layer height during the day (add cell_methods attribute: 'time: maximum')

mc_day-ap-tav-l-hxy.comment: The net mass flux should represent the difference between the updraft and downdraft components.  The flux is computed as the mass divided by the area of the grid cell.

mc_mon-ap-tav-l-hxy.comment: The net mass flux should represent the difference between the updraft and downdraft components.  The flux is computed as the mass divided by the area of the grid cell.

mc_subhr-ap-tpt-l-hxy.comment: The net mass flux should represent the difference between the updraft and downdraft components.  The flux is computed as the mass divided by the area of the grid cell.

mc_subhr-ap-tpt-l-hxys.comment: The net mass flux should represent the difference between the updraft and downdraft components.  The flux is computed as the mass divided by the area of the grid cell.

mcd_mon-ap-tav-l-hxy.comment: Calculated as the convective mass flux divided by the area of the whole grid cell (not just the area of the cloud).

mcu_mon-ap-tav-l-hxy.comment: In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics. The atmosphere convective mass flux is the vertical transport of mass for a field of cumulus clouds or thermals, given by the product of air density and vertical velocity. For an area-average, cell_methods should specify whether the average is over all the area or the area of updrafts only.

md_mon-ap-tav-l-hxy.comment: Emission from a primary source located anywhere within the atmosphere, including at the lower boundary (i.e. the surface of the earth).

meanage_mon-ae-tav-p39-hy.comment: The mean age of air is defined as the mean time that a stratospheric air mass has been out of contact with the well-mixed troposphere.

mfo_mon-op-tav-z0-ht.comment: Transport across_line means that which crosses a particular line on the Earth's surface; formally this means the integral along the line of the normal component of the transport.

minpblz_day-ae-tav-z0-hxy.comment: minimum boundary layer height during the day (add cell_methods attribute: 'time: minimum')

mlotst_mon-op-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean

mlotstmax_mon-op-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Maximum Ocean Mixed Layer Thickness Defined by Sigma T

mlotstmin_mon-op-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Sigma T is potential density referenced to ocean surface.

mlotstsq_mon-op-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
mlotstsq_mon-op-tav-z0-hxy.comment: The phrase 'square_of_X' means X*X. The ocean mixed layer is the upper part of the ocean, regarded as being well-mixed. The base of the mixed layer defined by 'temperature', 'sigma', 'sigma_theta', 'sigma_t' or vertical diffusivity is the level at which the quantity indicated differs from its surface value by a certain amount. A coordinate variable or scalar coordinate variable with standard name sea_water_sigma_t_difference can be used to specify the sigma_t criterion that determines the layer thickness. Sigma-t of sea water is the density of water at atmospheric pressure (i.e. the surface) having the same temperature and salinity, minus 1000 kg m-3. 'Thickness' means the vertical extent of a layer.
mlotstsq_mon-op-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Square of Ocean Mixed Layer Thickness Defined by Sigma T

mmraerh2o_mon-ae-tav-l-hxy.comment: Mass fraction is used in the construction mass_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y. It means the ratio of the mass of X to the mass of Y (including X). 'Aerosol' means the system of suspended liquid or solid particles in air (except cloud droplets) and their carrier gas, the air itself. 'Ambient_aerosol' means that the aerosol is measured or modelled at the ambient state of pressure, temperature and relative humidity that exists in its immediate environment. 'Ambient aerosol particles' are aerosol particles that have taken up ambient water through hygroscopic growth. The extent of hygroscopic growth depends on the relative humidity and the composition of the particles.

The sum of the quantities with standard names wood_debris_mass_content_of_nitrogen, surface_litter_mass_content_of_nitrogen and subsurface_litter_mass_content_of_nitrogen is the total nitrogen mass content of dead plant material.

The precise distinction between 'fine' and 'coarse' is model dependent. 'Subsurface litter' means the part of the litter mixed within the soil below the surface. The sum of the quantities with standard names wood_debris_mass_content_of_nitrogen, surface_litter_mass_content_of_nitrogen and subsurface_litter_mass_content_of_nitrogen is the total nitrogen mass content of dead plant material.
nLitterSubSurf_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Nitrogen Mass in Below-Ground Litter (non CWD)

nLitterSurf_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
nLitterSurf_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: 'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area. 'Litter' is dead plant material in or above the soil. It is distinct from coarse wood debris. The precise distinction between 'fine' and 'coarse' is model dependent. 'Surface litter' means the part of the litter resting above the soil surface. The sum of the quantities with standard names wood_debris_mass_content_of_nitrogen, surface_litter_mass_content_of_nitrogen and subsurface_litter_mass_content_of_nitrogen is the total nitrogen mass content of dead plant material.
nLitterSurf_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Nitrogen Mass in Above-Ground Litter (non CWD)

nbp_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
nbp_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: This is the net mass flux of carbon from atmosphere into land, calculated as photosynthesis MINUS the sum of  plant and soil respiration, carbon fluxes from fire, harvest, grazing  and land use change. Positive flux is into the land.
nbp_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux out of Atmosphere Due to Net Biospheric Production on Land [kgC m-2 s-1]

necbLut_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Computed as npp minus heterotrophic respiration minus fire minus C leaching minus harvesting/clearing. Positive rate is into the land, negative rate is from the land.  Do not include fluxes from anthropogenic product pools to atmosphere
necbLut_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Net Carbon Mass Flux into Land-Use Tile [kgC m-2 s-1]

nep_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
nep_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Natural flux of CO2 (expressed as a mass flux of carbon) from the atmosphere to the land calculated as the difference between uptake associated will photosynthesis and the release of CO2 from the sum of plant and soil respiration and fire.  Positive flux is into the land.  Emissions from natural fires and human ignition fires as calculated by the fire module of the dynamic vegetation model, but excluding any CO2 flux from fire included in fLuc (CO2 Flux to Atmosphere from Land Use Change).
nep_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Net Carbon Mass Flux out of Atmosphere Due to Net Ecosystem Productivity on Land [kgC m-2 s-1]

netAtmosLandC13Flux_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
netAtmosLandC13Flux_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Flux of carbon 31as carbon dioxide into the land. This flux should be reproducible by differencing the sum of all carbon pools (cVeg, cLitter, cSoil, and cProducts or equivalently cLand) from one time step to the next, except in the case of lateral transfer of carbon due to harvest, riverine transport of dissolved organic and/or inorganic carbon, or any other process (in which case the lateral_carbon_transfer_over_land term, see below, will be zero data).-
netAtmosLandC13Flux_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Net Mass Flux of 13C Between Atmosphere and Land (Positive into Land) as a Result of All Processes [kgC m-2 s-1]

netAtmosLandC14Flux_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
netAtmosLandC14Flux_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Flux of carbon-14 as carbon dioxide into the land. This flux should be reproducible by differencing the sum of all carbon pools (cVeg, cLitter, cSoil, and cProducts or equivalently cLand) from one time step to the next, except in the case of lateral transfer of carbon due to harvest, riverine transport of dissolved organic and/or inorganic carbon, or any other process (in which case the lateral_carbon_transfer_over_land term, see below, will be zero data).
netAtmosLandC14Flux_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Net Mass Flux of 14C Between Atmosphere and Land (Positive into Land) as a Result of All Processes [kgC m-2 s-1]

netAtmosLandCO2Flux_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
netAtmosLandCO2Flux_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: Flux of carbon as carbon dioxide into the land. This flux should be reproducible by differencing the sum of all carbon pools (cVeg, cLitter, cSoil, and cProducts or equivalently cLand) from one time step to the next, except in the case of lateral transfer of carbon due to harvest, riverine transport of dissolved organic and/or inorganic carbon, or any other process (in which case the lateral_carbon_transfer_over_land term, see below, will be zero data).
netAtmosLandCO2Flux_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Net Flux of CO2 Between Atmosphere and Land (Positive into Land) as a Result of All Processes [kgC m-2 s-1]

npp_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
npp_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: 'Production of carbon' means the production of biomass expressed as the mass of carbon which it contains. Net primary production is the excess of gross primary production (rate of synthesis of biomass from inorganic precursors) by autotrophs ('producers'), for example, photosynthesis in plants or phytoplankton, over the rate at which the autotrophs themselves respire some of this biomass. 'Productivity' means production per unit area. The phrase 'expressed_as' is used in the construction A_expressed_as_B, where B is a chemical constituent of A. It means that the quantity indicated by the standard name is calculated solely with respect to the B contained in A, neglecting all other chemical constituents of A.
npp_mon-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Net Primary Production on Land as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

nudgincsm_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
nudgincsm_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: A nudging increment refers to an amount added to parts of a model system. The phrase 'nudging_increment_in_X' refers to an increment in quantity X over a time period which should be defined in the bounds of the time coordinate. 'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area. 'Water' means water in all phases. The mass content of water in soil refers to the vertical integral from the surface down to the bottom of the soil model. The 'soil content' of a quantity refers to the vertical integral from the surface down to the bottom of the soil model. For the content between specified levels in the soil, standard names including 'content_of_soil_layer' are used.
nudgincsm_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Nudging Increment of Water in Soil Moisture

nudgincswe_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where land time: mean
nudgincswe_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.comment: A nudging increment refers to an amount added to parts of a model system. The phrase 'nudging_increment_in_X' refers to an increment in quantity X over a time period which should be defined in the bounds of the time coordinate. The surface called 'surface' means the lower boundary of the atmosphere. 'Amount' means mass per unit area. 'Snow and ice on land' means ice in glaciers, ice caps, ice sheets & shelves, river and lake ice, any other ice on a land surface, such as frozen flood water, and snow lying on such ice or on the land surface.
nudgincswe_day-ld-tav-z0-hxy.long_name: Nudging Increment of Water in Snow

A chemical or biological species denoted by X may be described by a single term such as 'nitrogen' or a phrase such as 'nox_expressed_as_nitrogen'.

o2_yr-oc-tav-l-hxy.comment: 'Mole concentration' means number of moles per unit volume, also called 'molarity', and is used in the construction mole_concentration_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y. o2min_mon-oc-tav-z0-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
o2min_mon-oc-tav-z0-hxy.comment: 'Mole concentration' means number of moles per unit volume, also called 'molarity', and is used in the construction mole_concentration_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.  A chemical or biological species denoted by X may be described by a single term such as 'nitrogen' or a phrase such as 'nox_expressed_as_nitrogen'. The concentration of any chemical species, whether particulate or dissolved, may vary with depth in the ocean.  A depth profile may go through one or more local minima in concentration. The mole_concentration_of_molecular_oxygen_in_sea_water_at_shallowest_local_minimum_in_vertical_profile is the mole concentration of oxygen at the local minimum in the concentration profile that occurs closest to the sea surface.

ocontemprmadvect_mon-op-tav-l-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
ocontemprmadvect_mon-op-tav-l-hxy.comment: Conservative Temperature is defined as part of the Thermodynamic Equation of Seawater 2010 (TEOS-10) which was adopted in 2010 by the International Oceanographic Commission (IOC). The phrase 'residual mean advection' refers to the sum of the model's resolved advective transport plus any parameterized advective transport. Parameterized advective transport includes processes such as parameterized mesoscale and submesoscale transport, as well as any other advectively parameterized transport. When the parameterized advective transport is represented in the model as a skew-diffusion rather than an advection, then the parameterized skew diffusion should be included in this diagnostic, since the convergence of skew-fluxes are identical (in the continuous formulation) to the convergence of advective fluxes.
ocontemprmadvect_mon-op-tav-l-hxy.long_name: Tendency of Sea Water Conservative Temperature Expressed as Heat Content Due to Residual Mean Advection

Parameterized advective transport includes processes such as parameterized mesoscale and submesoscale transport, as well as any other advectively parameterized transport. When the parameterized advective transport is represented in the model as a skew-diffusion rather than an advection, then the parameterized skew diffusion should be included in this diagnostic, since the convergence of skew-fluxes are identical (in the continuous formulation) to the convergence of advective fluxes.

pabigthetao_mon-op-tav-l-hxy.cell_methods: area: mean where sea time: mean
pabigthetao_mon-op-tav-l-hxy.comment: A passive tracer in an ocean model whose surface flux does not come from the atmosphere but is imposed externally upon the simulated climate system. The surface flux is expressed as a heat flux and converted to a passive tracer increment as if it were a heat flux being added to conservative temperature. The passive tracer is transported within the ocean as if it were conservative temperature. The passive tracer is zero in the control climate of the model.
